      <hedline>
        <hl1>Back Seat for Peace</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jutta Maue Kay letter, commenting on August 26 article, scores absence of Dalai Lama from UN's Millennium World Peace Summit of Religious and Spiritual Leaders because of pressure from China</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>For the United Nations to exclude the Dalai Lama because of pressure from China invalidates the whole purpose of the Millennium World Peace Summit of Religious and Spiritual Leaders (Public Lives column, Aug. 26).</p>
        <p>I cannot think of anybody who has dedicated his whole life and worked harder for peace in this world than the Dalai Lama.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>For the United Nations to exclude the Dalai Lama because of pressure from China invalidates the whole purpose of the Millennium World Peace Summit of Religious and Spiritual Leaders (Public Lives column, Aug. 26).</p>
        <p>I cannot think of anybody who has dedicated his whole life and worked harder for peace in this world than the Dalai Lama.</p>
        <p>As a longtime supporter of the United Nations, I am more than disappointed. It seems that peace has to take a back seat to business and politics, even at its own summit meeting.</p>
        <p>JUTTA MAUE KAY  Franklin, Tenn., Aug. 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
